## **4. Critical Open Items (do these next)** 

## **4.1 Fix the navigation — this is the #1 ROI item** 

The nav today reads: Home · About Us · Services · Why Rwanda · FAQ · Reservations · Blogs · English · Contact us. "Services" is a dropdown trigger, but its dropdown contents do not include the dedicated landing pages — a foreign-investor visitor who clicks Services either lands on the generic /services page or sees a dropdown that still only points to legacy URLs. The homepage service cards have the same problem. **Target nav:** Home · Why Rwanda · Services ▾ (Business Registration · Investment Advisory · HR & Recruitment · Relocation · Executive Travel) · About · Insights · FAQ · Reservations · Contact · [Book Free Consultation] (gold button). The "Book Free Consultation" CTA should be a visually distinct gold #C9A84C button, not a text link, and should point to /contact?service=consultation (or a future /book-consultation page). 

## **4.2 Resolve /gallery vs /explore-rwanda duplication** 

Both URLs return byte-identical HTML (1,964 chars, identical title, meta description, canonical). Pick one canonical — recommend /explore-rwanda — and 301-redirect the other. Until this is fixed, Google will likely split ranking signal between the two URLs, and may classify one as duplicate content. 

## **4.3 Reservations URL case sensitivity** 

The nav links to /Reservations (capital R). /reservations (lowercase) returns 404. URL routing should be caseinsensitive, or at minimum a 301 from lowercase → canonical. Most users typing the URL by hand will use lowercase. 

## **4.4 SSR the /contact and /blogs pages** 

Both pages currently render their content payload client-side. /contact ships only "Loading…" in static HTML; /blogs ships filter chips but no post cards. For SEO, page speed, and accessibility, these two pages benefit most from static generation. The blog index can be statically generated nightly from the existing sitemap source. 

