## **5. Reservations — Implementation Advisory (Deferred Build)** 

Per your direction, Reservations is being redesigned to mirror the experience of standard booking platforms (Booking.com / Agoda for accommodation, Klook / GetYourGuide for tours, Uber-style for transport). The model you described is a **hybrid two-path flow:** (A) Browse-and-book — customers see your listed providers, filter, reserve directly; (B) Describe-your-need — customers explain what they want and Bonet's team handles the rest. The recommendations below assume that hybrid model. 

## **5.1 Recommended architecture** 

**Two entry points on /reservations:** two large cards on landing — "Browse & Book" (image of hotel/car/itinerary) and "Tell us what you need" (image of a concierge). Either path lands the user in a structured intake; both end with a confirmation email + WhatsApp ping to the Bonet ops desk. 

## **Path A — Browse & Book (the platform-like path)** 

- Category selector first: Hotels & Apartments · Transport · Tours & Experiences · Conference & Events. Keep categories small at launch — fewer than five — and expand as supply grows. 

- For each category, show a provider card grid: cover image, name, location, price band (RWF / USD), star rating or Bonet-verified badge, "View & Book" button. 

- Provider detail page: photo gallery, description (you write), amenities, price table, availability calendar, "Reserve Now" form. 

- Reservation form should be progressive: select dates/quantity → guest info → confirm. Do NOT take card payment on day one — collect the request and contact via WhatsApp to confirm + invoice. 

- Each provider needs a clean CMS record: name, category, photos[], location, base price, currency, included, excluded, cancellation policy, contact internal. 

**Path B — Describe Your Need (the concierge path)** 

- Simple form, five fields: What do you need? (free text) · When? (date or range) · How many people? · Approximate budget (optional) · Preferred contact (WhatsApp / Email / Phone). 

- Suggested categories as quick-pick chips above the free-text box (Hotel · Transport · Tour · Event · Other) — captures common intent without forcing taxonomy. 

- Auto-confirmation: "Muraho! We've received your request. A Bonet concierge will respond within 4 working hours." 

- Internal: route to ops Slack/WhatsApp channel with the form payload + a single-click "Claim" button for the on-duty concierge. 

## **5.2 Technical build sequence (suggested)** 

- Phase 1 (1–2 weeks): launch Path B only. It is just a form + a routing webhook. Zero inventory work. Captures real demand and gives you data on what people actually ask for. 

- Phase 2 (2–4 weeks): launch Path A for one or two categories where you already have supplier relationships (start with Hotels & Transport — highest request volume). 

- Phase 3 (later): expand Path A categories, add availability calendars, and only then introduce card payments via Flutterwave or DPO. 

## **5.3 Business considerations** 

- Commission vs. markup: decide upfront whether you charge the customer a markup (transparent listed price = your selling price) or take a back-end commission from the provider. The former lets you control conversion and trust. 

Bonet Elite Services — Final Site Audit v3 — 3 June 2026 — Page 6 

- Cancellation policy: write one default cancellation window per category and surface it on every booking card. Foreign clients will not commit without that clarity. 

- Provider vetting: build a checklist (insurance, licensing, references, on-site visit) and put a small "Bonet Verified" badge on listings that pass. This is a real differentiator vs. raw OTAs. 

- Currency: list prices in both RWF and USD; let the user toggle. Almost no foreign-investor traffic will convert from RWF-only pricing. 

- Reviews: don't launch with reviews; launch with editorial blurbs you write yourself. Add reviews after 50+ completed bookings — empty 0-review listings hurt conversion. 

## **5.4 Visual & UX guidance** 

- Mirror the dual-CTA hero pattern used by Klook and GetYourGuide: hero image + "Browse Services" + "Tell us what you need" buttons side by side. 

- Keep the existing Bonet visual identity — navy + gold, generous whitespace. Avoid OTA-style red "book now" urgency banners; they undercut the premium positioning. 

- Mobile-first: 60%+ of reservation requests will be from phones. Provider detail pages must be onethumb scrollable, with the "Reserve" button sticky at the bottom on mobile. 

## **6. Strategic Notes Beyond the Audit** 

**Site voice is now consistent on the new landing pages but fragmented on the legacy URLs.** A visitor's first impression depends on which URL Google sends them to. Fixing the nav and redirecting the legacy pages turns your weakest pages into a single coherent funnel. 

**FAQ at 56 questions is a real SEO weapon — use it.** Each question is a long-tail keyword. Consider /faq/[slug] permalinks for the highest-volume questions so each gets its own indexable page (e.g. /faq/how-long-toregister-company-in-rwanda). 

**Add a single "What we don't do" note on /services.** Premium positioning is partly defined by what you decline. A short paragraph ("We are not an OTA, an immigration lawyer, or a real-estate broker — we coordinate with vetted specialists in each") signals seriousness and pre-qualifies leads. 

**Tie the blog to the funnel.** Every blog post should end with a tile linking to one of the five landing pages relevant to its topic. With 53 posts and growing, this is the biggest internal-link asset you have. 

